Police in Limpopo have arrested five suspects in connection with the bus petrol bomb attack where six miners were killed. Following the incident, the police had established a level task team of investigators that comprised of the Hawks to track down the suspects after a bus was bombed in Burgersfort. The bus was transporting mine workers who were returning home from a night shift on Monday at around 20h00 pm. The police said that when the bus stopped at Driekop bus station, two unknown suspects got into the bus and set it alight using a highly flammable liquid. The suspects then jumped out of the bus that was already engulfed in huge flames. “Police investigations are still continuing and more arrests cannot be ruled out,” the police said. The bus was carrying 50 mine workers when it was bombed, 28 of them were taken to hospital after suffering burn wounds. Out of the six miners that passed away, four were men and 2 were women. Provincial Commissioner Lieutenant General Nneke Ledwaba has commended the members of the task team for the sterling work and the speed it took to solve the matter. The police also said that they have started with the process of identifying the six deceased who were burnt. The suspects will appear at the Mecklenburg magistrates court on Thursday. -TNA Reporter     